05704nam a22006375i 9780228013761DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280137617 a10.1515/97802280137612doi  a(DE-B1597)655208  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aART0150402bisacsh00aThrough Post-Atomic Eyes /ced. by John O'Brian, Claudette Lauzon. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (496 p.) :b158 photos, 3 maps, colour throughout  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Beaverbrook Canadian Foundation Studies in Art History ;v2900tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: To See through Post-Atomic Eyes -- tNuclear Afterimages -- tGodzilla’s Breath -- tPort Hope in the Era of Nuclear Waste -- tPost-Atomic Childhood around 1980 -- tFlashblindness -- tBeyond the Bomb -- tBelow the Bombs -- tBig Data? No Thanks -- tLittle Boys and Blue Skies: Drones through Post-Atomic Eyes -- tHiroshima after Fukushima -- tThrough the Lens of Fukushima -- tAs If Nothing Happened, As If Everything Is the Same: Composure in the Wake of Fukushima -- tThe Blindspot of the Post-Atomic -- tAtomic Anthropocene -- tThe Half-Life of Yasser Arafat -- tThe Future-Past, the Future-Present, the Future-Possible: The Chernobyl Exclusion Zone Photographs of David McMillan -- tTroubling Time/s and Ecologies of Nothingness -- tIllustrations -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat does it mean to live in a post-atomic world? Photography and contemporary art offer a provocative lens through which to comprehend the by-products of the atomic age, from weapons proliferation, nuclear disaster, and aerial surveillance to toxic waste disposal and climate change. Confronting cultural fallout from the dawn of the nuclear age, Through Post-Atomic Eyes addresses the myriad iterations of nuclear threat and their visual legacy in the twentieth and twenty-first centuries. Whether in the iconic black-and-white photograph of a mushroom cloud rising over Nagasaki in 1945 or in the steady stream of real-time video documenting the 2011 meltdown at the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear power plant, atomic culture - and our understanding of it - is inextricably constructed by the visual. This book takes the image as its starting point to address the visual inheritance of atomic anxieties; the intersection of photography, nuclear industries, and military technocultures; and the complex temporality of nuclear technologies. Contemporary artists contribute lens-based works that explore the consequences of the nuclear, and its afterlives, in the Anthropocene. Revealing, through both art and prose, startling new connections between the ongoing threat of nuclear catastrophe and current global crises, Through Post-Atomic Eyes is a richly illustrated examination of how photography shapes and is shaped by nuclear culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aART / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBarad, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBridle, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCazdyn, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarish, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzpatrick, Blake, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Lindsey A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregory, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLauzon, Claudette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.